<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RALPH VARTABEDIAN and Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 PAY UP: More than 12,000 Ventura County residents neglected to file state 
income tax returns for 1993. . . . You know who you are. . . . But just in case 
you don't, the state Franchise Tax Board in January will mail "friendly 
reminders" to you and more than 600,000 other residents across the state who 
failed to file. Tardy taxpayers will be given 30 days to fork over any amount 
owed or face fees and a minimum penalty of $114. . . . Or, they should send a 
letter to the state explaining why they don't have to file. 
</P>
<P>
 PINK DEATH?: It's been a trusty heartburn remedy for years. . . . Now, 
Pepto-Bismol may be useful on an entirely different front: in the war against 
the Medfly. Scientists have concocted a spray, made from a dye found in the 
bright pink liquid, that zaps the insects dead (A3). The spray could eventually 
replace malathion, a pesticide being doused on Camarillo in the effort to wipe 
out a Medfly infestation. . . . Malathion opponents are tickled pink. "We're 
delighted by the whole idea," said Leonard Mehlmauer of GASP, or Group Against 
Spraying People. 
</P>
<P>
 AMGEN ARRESTS: Two men have been charged in a Boston industrial-espionage case 
involving Epogen, a genetically engineered drug produced by Amgen Inc., the 
Thousand Oaks-based biotechnology giant (D2). . . . The men allegedly tried to 
sell the drug, which stimulates production of red blood cells and is widely 
used by kidney dialysis and AIDS patients, to an FBI agent posing as a Russian 
government official. 
</P>
<P>
 LIGHTING THE WAY: If a police car with its headlights on pulls up behind you 
today, it may not necessarily mean that you're about to get a ticket. . . . 
Authorities across the county are taking part in "Lights On for Life." The 
annual observance honors people killed or injured in drug- and alcohol-related 
accidents -- and aims to caution drinkers not to get behind the wheel. Drunk 
drivers are "always a problem" during the holidays, the California Highway 
Patrol said. Tax Bite 
</P>
<P>
 Number of Ventura County residents who failed to file 1993 state income tax 
returns: 
</P>
<P>
 Thousands Oaks: 1,530 
</P>
<P>
 Simi Valley: 1,266 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo: 1,178 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura: 1,140 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard: 1,126 
</P>
<P>
 Port Hueneme: 561 
</P>
<P>
 Moorpark: 456 
</P>
<P>
 Ojal: 342 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Paula: 288 
</P>
<P>
 Fillmore: 128 
</P>
<P>
 Source: California Franchise Tax Board Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</TEXT>
