<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The amount of trash entering Orange County landfills has steadily declined 
since 1989, according to the county's Integrated Waste Management Department. 
The decline occurred because most cities have adopted successful recycling 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, residents and businesses are putting out less trash because they 
were making fewer purchases due to the recession, officials said. It's only 
recently that the economy has shown signs of improving. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1993-94, the amount of trash taken to the county's four landfills was 1.3 
million tons less than in 1988-89. This should be good news to cities that are 
anxious to comply with a state law that requires a 25% reduction in the volume 
of trash dumped in landfills by 1995. Today 
</P>
<P>
 "Music of Many Lands" is the theme of the 32nd annual Cruise of Lights in 
Huntington Harbour. Narrated boat rides through the harbor to view the bright 
and festive decorated homes will continue tonight through Dec. 22. 
</P>
<P>
 Tickets are $8.50 and $9.50 for adults and $5 for children. 
</P>
<P>
 The event is sponsored by Huntington Harbour Philharmonic Committee. Proceeds 
go toward music education programs throughout Orange County. Information: (714) 
840-7542. 
</P>
