<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOU CAN'T GO WRONG WITH THESE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CONNIE KOENENN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Timed for holiday shopping, the December Consumer Reports is a roundup of best 
buys in gifts. 
</P>
<P>
 "We work on this all year," says staffer Jeffrey Asher."It focuses on the best 
we have tested, as well as the products we think are appropriate for the 
holidays -- it would probably not be a steam iron for your wife." 
</P>
<P>
 In large gift categories, the magazine's testers report on games, toys, TV/VCR 
combos, stereo components, compact cameras, boom boxes, cordless phones, 
phone-answering machines and sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
 As a bonus, the issue opens with some "Holiday Tidbits," including: 
</P>
<P>
 * Best color-print film for shooting family pictures: Most of the major brands 
in ISO 100. 
</P>
<P>
 * Best antacids after you've eaten too much: Mylanta Double Strength and 
Maalox Plus Extra Strength, with Alka-Seltzer tablets close behind. Best road 
atlas if you're going to Grandma's house: The $8.95 Rand McNally. 
</P>
<P>
 * Best way to shop for a Christmas tree: Slide your hand along the branches to 
make sure the needles don't come off, sniff for fragrance and be sure it's 
green. 
</P>
<P>
 * The best wishes from Ebenezer: Try to avoid the tempting offer from stores 
and credit-card companies to skip the December payment. With accruing interest 
rates it's like taking out a loan at 10% to 18% interest. CONNIE KOENENN 
</P>
</TEXT>
